<p><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000" style="font-size: 12.8px;"><b>What is the Paris Climate Agreement?&nbsp;</b><br><br>The Paris Climate Agreement is a global deal where 195 countries agreed to reduce their carbon emissions to address the catastrophic impact of climate change. Signed in December 2015, the Paris agreement committed the vast majority of the international community to reducing 28 percent of their carbon emission output by 2025.&nbsp;<br><br><b>Why is pulling out dangerous?</b><br><br>1)&nbsp;<b>&nbsp;Trump would further diminish American credibility abroad.</b>&nbsp;"This would be a colossal mistake.It would also devastate our international credibility. We are one of the two largest carbon emitters, with China. We are the ones who put this deal together. It is the first step to try to do something about climate change. For President Trump to take us out, it is anti-science," said Former under secretary of state Nick Burns of the Republican Bush administration.&nbsp; The&nbsp;U.S. would join only two other countries Nicaragua and Syria in holding out on the accord.&nbsp;<br><br>2)&nbsp;<b>Pulling out will seriously speed up the effects of Global Warming.</b>&nbsp;<a href="https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/an-open-letter-from-scientists-to-president-elect-trump-on-climate-change/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/an-open-letter-from-scientists-to-president-elect-trump-on-climate-change/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEf1CfC9YGsjPLg7CIA3PUKt-1jnQ" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">Scientific consensus,</a>&nbsp;again and again, points to rising seas, flooded coastal cities, mass extinction, searing drought, human displacement, migration crises, deadlier heatwaves, crop failures, and stronger storms.&nbsp; In the past 5 years alone, storms, floods, droughts, and wildfires caused over $250 billion in damages to American taxpayers<a href="http://www.cpr.org/news/story/cu-researcher-one-of-hundreds-of-scientists-imploring-trump-on-climate-change" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://www.cpr.org/news/story/cu-researcher-one-of-hundreds-of-scientists-imploring-trump-on-climate-change&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEgHowQj2IYpH9dKLaBPA3YjWdKnA" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">http://www.cpr.org/<wbr>news/story/cu-researcher-one-<wbr>of-hundreds-of-scientists-<wbr>imploring-trump-on-climate-<wbr>change</a>. This number will grow exponentially if nothing changes.The U.S. and China&nbsp;<i>combined&nbsp;</i>account for 45 percent of the world's carbon emissions. While China has pledged to remain committed to the accord regardless of Trump's decision, it is not clear if other countries would walk away with U.S. participation.&nbsp;<br><b><br>Is Trump's withdrawal a sure thing?&nbsp;</b><br><br>On May 31, two sources within the Trump administration told Axios that Trump had decided to pull the U.S. out of the Paris agreement while the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Administrator Scott Pruitt depicted withdrawal details.<br><br>It has not been determined whether the U.S. would fully withdraw from the accord over the course of three years or to pull from the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.&nbsp; Established in 1992, the UNFCCC treaty was the foundation of the Paris Agreement that had been initiated by the Obama administration. If Trump decided to opt out of the treaty, the U.S. would renounce its international commitment to environmental protection, according to the BBC.<br><br><b>Who is supporting withdrawal?</b></font></p><div style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px;"><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><span style="background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">Leaders and lobbyists from coal-producing states have pressed Trump to &nbsp;cancel US promises to the agreement, spurred by ulterior motives to reduce regulations around cole and encourage carbon emitting products, lining the pockets of the coal industry.&nbsp; Republicans like&nbsp;<a href="http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/opinions/withdraw-paris-accord-opinion-cruz/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/opinions/withdraw-paris-accord-opinion-cruz/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGAS2LpUnTuVD9_87hlMS8P1DUqKQ" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">Senator Ted Cruz</a>&nbsp;cite the right wing think tank&nbsp;</span><span style="background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">National Economic Research Associates Economic Consulting study: &nbsp;"The Paris Agreement could obliterate&nbsp;</span><a href="http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHVDreoc-v-Xwh0is4Wz2sca0YZ2w" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration-line: none; background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">$3 trillion of GDP,</a><span style="background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">&nbsp;6.5 million industrial sector jobs and $7,000 in per capita household income from the American economy by 2040. Meeting the 2025 emissions reduction target alone could subtract&nbsp;</span><a href="http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHVDreoc-v-Xwh0is4Wz2sca0YZ2w" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration-line: none; background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">$250 billion from our GDP</a><span style="background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">&nbsp;and eliminate 2.7 million jobs. The cement, iron and steel, and petroleum refining industries could see their&nbsp;</span><a href="http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://accf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/170316-NERA-ACCF-Full-Report.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHVDreoc-v-Xwh0is4Wz2sca0YZ2w" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); box-sizing: border-box; text-decoration-line: none; background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">production cut</a><span style="background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);">&nbsp;by 21% 19%, and 11% respectively."</span></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000">However, in an open letter from Fortune 100 companies, business leaders make a strong case for the business benefits from the Agreement.&nbsp; American companies are well positioned to benefit from growing global markets in clean technologies, generating domestic jobs and growth.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.c2es.org/docUploads/business-letter-white-house-paris-agreement-final-04-26-2017.pdf" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.c2es.org/docUploads/business-letter-white-house-paris-agreement-final-04-26-2017.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGVi2ZGYrVgXYcoP1PxvOP_asI0fg" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">&nbsp;Pulling</a><a href="https://www.c2es.org/docUploads/business-letter-white-house-paris-agreement-final-04-26-2017.pdf" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.c2es.org/docUploads/business-letter-white-house-paris-agreement-final-04-26-2017.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGVi2ZGYrVgXYcoP1PxvOP_asI0fg" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">&nbsp;out of the agreement could subject the United States to retaliatory trade measures, enabling other countries to leapfrog American industry.</a><br><br><b>What do American voters think about this?</b><br><br>Sixty-seven percent of registered voters were concerned about the impact of climate change, including 50 percent of Republican respondents, according to a&nbsp;<span class="aBn" data-term="goog_644095057" tabindex="0" style="border-bottom: 1px dashed rgb(204, 204, 204); position: relative; top: -2px; z-index: 0;"><span class="aQJ" style="position: relative; top: 2px; z-index: -1;">April 10</span></span>&nbsp;Morning Consult/ Politico poll.&nbsp; The important question here is&nbsp;<i>how</i>&nbsp;many of these voters reside in swing state districts and&nbsp;<i>how many</i>&nbsp;of these voters will remember this during the 2018 mid-term elections and 2020 presidential election.<br><br><b>What can YOU do?</b></font><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000">1. Sign&nbsp;<a href="https://www.change.org/p/tell-trump-to-actonclimate" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.change.org/p/tell-trump-to-actonclimate&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNFrvn-iY7MZJWbOQ9IOLhuXphDBlA" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">this petition</a>&nbsp;to show politicians in Washington, D.C. people like you OPPOSE a withdrawal. &nbsp;</font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000">2. Make a small contribution to organizations that could STOP Trump.&nbsp; The Natural Resources Defense Council will go to court to block the Trump administration from rolling back protections against dangerous air pollution from the oil and gas industry.&nbsp;Click here to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nrdc.org/media/2017/170531" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.nrdc.org/media/2017/170531&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNFdwl9xuqWbfiMKQToGP7zcigQHjg" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">donate</a>.</font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000">3.&nbsp;<a href="http://nypost.com/2017/05/31/trump-expected-to-pull-out-of-paris-climate-deal/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://nypost.com/2017/05/31/trump-expected-to-pull-out-of-paris-climate-deal/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215897000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGkkHunA-tF1J4tbzboK1EYuMWk4A" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">Department of Energy Secretary Rick Perry and Secretary of State Rex Tillerson</a>&nbsp;are&nbsp;pushing Trump to stay.&nbsp; Send a quick letter of support for the Paris Climate Agreement by contacting the&nbsp;<a href="https://energy.gov/contact-us" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://energy.gov/contact-us&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215898000&amp;usg=AFQjCNFYA0ODmCBTrNuPbU0wWXH1y1gneg" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">Department of Energy</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://register.state.gov/contactus/contactusform" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://register.state.gov/contactus/contactusform&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215898000&amp;usg=AFQjCNF7P28DeqoGXxehTizBWScvHi7fIg" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">Department of State.</a>&nbsp; I have worked in a an elected official's office, and staff keep track of comments and relay them to the head.</font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000">Other Sources:&nbsp;</font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/09/opinion/the-business-case-for-the-paris-climate-accord.html?_r=0" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/09/opinion/the-business-case-for-the-paris-climate-accord.html?_r%3D0&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215898000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGxIxC72bzx9WcabvSL8KJVGMNS5A" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">https://www.nytimes.com/2017/<wbr>05/09/opinion/the-business-<wbr>case-for-the-paris-climate-<wbr>accord.html?_r=0</a></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><a href="http://www.npr.org/2017/05/31/530890143/trump-has-multiple-escape-routes-from-paris-climate-accord" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://www.npr.org/2017/05/31/530890143/trump-has-multiple-escape-routes-from-paris-climate-accord&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1496379215898000&amp;usg=AFQjCNG3CwAzXuwr64hVjFniDts2VoUKXQ" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204);">http://www.npr.org/2017/05/31/<wbr>530890143/trump-has-multiple-<wbr>escape-routes-from-paris-<wbr>climate-accord</a>ï»¿</font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br /></font></div><div><font face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color="#000000"><br /></font></div></div></div>